 <table-wrap-foot>
  <p>*FDA-approved clinical specimens vary by specific test; refer to the manufacturer’s package insert for each test’s approved specimens</p>
  <p>**Recommended for testing hospitalized patients with suspected influenza. Some molecular assays also detect other respiratory pathogens</p>
  <p>#Patients with respiratory failure and suspected influenza should have lower respiratory tract specimens collected and tested, including if upper respiratory tract specimens are negative for influenza because a patient may have cleared influenza virus from the upper respiratory tract and continue to have influenza viral replication in the lower respiratory tract</p>
  <p>
   <italic>NP</italic> nasopharyngeal, 
   <italic>BAL</italic> bronchoalveolar lavage
  </p>
  <p>Serologic testing is not recommended for diagnosis or clinical management of patients with suspected influenza</p>
 </table-wrap-foot>
